================================================================================
SECTION 1: NOTIFICATION CHANNEL HUB UI PATTERNS
================================================================================

1.1 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
------------------------

A) SLACK NOTIFICATION HUB
- Three-tier hierarchy: Workspace > Channel > Thread level control
- Default notifications: "All new messages" OR "Mentions & DMs only"
- Exception system: Users can set per-channel overrides (e.g., #urgent always notifies)
- Keyword triggers: Custom words that generate notifications when mentioned
- Sound customization: Different sounds for different notification types
- What works: Granular control without overwhelming; defaults are sane
- What fails: Buried settings (too many clicks to find the right toggle)
- Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Mirror the exception-based model -- set sane defaults
  but let users promote specific categories to "always notify"

B) DISCORD SERVER NOTIFICATION SETTINGS
- Four notification levels: All Messages / Only @mentions / Nothing / Custom
- Notification Overrides: Per-category and per-channel override dropdown
- Mute durations: 15min / 1hr / 3hr / 8hr / 24hr / Until turned off
- Suppress @everyone and @here mentions toggle
- Mobile push: Mirrors desktop preferences OR can be set independently
- What works: The mute duration picker is brilliant for temporary quiet
- What fails: Notification Overrides dropdown can be overwhelming with many channels
- Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Offer temporary mute durations per-channel, not just on/off

C) WHATSAPP BUSINESS CHANNEL MANAGEMENT
- Channel Activity Notifications: Follower activity + Admin activity alerts
- Template system: Pre-approved message templates (utility, marketing, authentication)
- Notification tone customization per contact/group
- Media auto-download granular control (WiFi vs mobile data)
- What works: Simple binary choices (on/off) for most users
- What fails: No frequency control -- either all or nothing
- Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Frequency controls (immediate / daily digest / weekly)
  are a massive differentiator over WhatsApp

D) TELEGRAM NOTIFICATION SETTINGS
- Per-chat notification toggle (mute forever or for specific duration)
- Custom notification sound per chat
- Notification exceptions list (always notify even when muted)
- Smart Notifications: Combine frequent messages into batches
- Chat-specific LED colors on Android
- What works: Granularity without complexity via exception model
- What fails: Settings scattered across profile and settings screens
- Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Centralize all channel management in one hub screen

E) TODOIST NOTIFICATION PREFERENCES
- Grid-style layout: Rows = event types, Columns = channels (email, push)
- Per-project notification settings for shared projects
- Urgent Reminders (iOS): Full-screen alarm that breaks through DND and Silent mode
- Categories: Comments, task assignments, collaborator joins/leaves
- What works: Grid layout makes cross-channel comparison easy at a glance
- What fails: Limited channel types (only email + push)
- Key takeaway for UNJYNX: Use a matrix/grid layout for notification preferences
  but extend columns to 5+ channels (push, WhatsApp, Telegram, email, SMS)


1.2 DESIGN PATTERNS ANALYSIS
-----------------------------

PATTERN 1: HUB-AND-SPOKE MODEL
- Central "Channels" screen shows all connected channels with status
- Each channel card expands or navigates to detailed settings
- Pros: Excellent discoverability, single entry point
- Cons: Can feel like a long list if user has many channels
- Recommendation for UNJYNX: Primary pattern; use cards with status chips

PATTERN 2: CATEGORY-FIRST MODEL (SUPRSEND)
- Organize by notification category first (e.g., "Task Reminders", "Daily Content")
- Within each category, show channel toggles
- Three levels: Category on/off > Channel on/off > Frequency control
- Pros: Users think in terms of "what" they want, not "how" to receive it
- Cons: Users who want to disable all email must visit every category
- Recommendation for UNJYNX: Support BOTH views -- category-first + channel-first

PATTERN 3: MASTER TOGGLE + EXCEPTIONS
- Top-level master switch per channel (e.g., "WhatsApp: ON")
- Below: exception list of categories that deviate from master
- Pros: Fastest for bulk on/off; exception list is short
- Cons: Requires mental model of defaults vs exceptions
- Recommendation for UNJYNX: Use for the channel detail page

PATTERN 4: SMART DEFAULTS WITH PROGRESSIVE DISCLOSURE
- Onboarding: Choose a "mode" (Calm / Regular / Power User)
- Each mode pre-configures channels, frequency, and quiet hours
- Users can drill down to customize individual settings later
- Pros: Fast setup; reduces decision fatigue for new users
- Cons: Users may forget to customize later
- Recommendation for UNJYNX: MUST IMPLEMENT -- this is core to onboarding


1.3 INFORMATION ARCHITECTURE FOR CHANNEL HUB
----------------------------------------------

Recommended screen hierarchy for UNJYNX:

  Notification Hub (main)
  +-- Active Channels (grid of connected channels)
  |   +-- Push Notifications [always present]
  |   +-- WhatsApp [if connected]
  |   +-- Telegram [if connected]
  |   +-- Email [if connected]
  |   +-- SMS [if connected]
  |   +-- Instagram [if connected]
  |   +-- Discord [if connected]
  |   +-- Slack [if connected]
  +-- Add Channel (+ FAB or inline button)
  |   +-- Available channels with setup flow
  +-- Notification Preferences
  |   +-- Category-first view (matrix grid)
  |   +-- Channel-first view (toggle)
  +-- Quiet Hours / Focus Modes
  +-- Fallback Priority Chain
  +-- Usage & Quota

================================================================================
SECTION 2: QR CODE CONNECTION FLOW DESIGNS
================================================================================

2.1 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
------------------------

A) WHATSAPP WEB QR FLOW
- Step 1: Website generates Guest Token, displayed as QR code
- Step 2: Mobile app scans QR, retrieves Guest Token
- Step 3: Mobile Auth Token + Guest Token sent to Auth Service
- Step 4: Auth Service generates Web Auth Token
- Step 5: Web Auth Token sent to website via WebSocket
- Step 6: Website reinitializes with Web Auth Token
- UX flow: Open WhatsApp > Settings > Linked Devices > Link a Device > Scan QR
- What works: No typing credentials; instant sync; feels magical
- What fails: QR refreshes every 20 seconds (too fast for some users)
- Key takeaway: Token exchange pattern is gold standard for secure pairing

B) TELEGRAM QR CONNECTION
- Used for desktop/web login from mobile phone
- Also used for profile sharing with customizable QR code colors
- Steps: Profile > QR code icon > Customize > Share/Scan
- Uniquely allows QR code color customization to match brand
- What works: Dual purpose (login + contact sharing)
- What fails: Discovery -- many users don't know QR login exists
- Key takeaway: Let users customize QR code appearance (brand colors)

C) SIGNAL QR DEVICE LINKING
- Primary phone scans QR displayed on secondary device
- Process is deliberately simple -- single scan, automatic sync
- Requires PIN verification after scan for extra security
- User issue identified: "Open in browser" label confused users after scanning
- What works: Simplest flow of all three -- one scan, done
- What fails: Error messages when scan fails are not clear enough
- Key takeaway: Clear error states and retry instructions are essential

D) LINE QR LOGIN
- QR code has 5-minute expiry with visible countdown timer
- Auto-verification after scan with push notification confirmation
- "Identity verification" dialog on phone with approve/deny buttons
- What works: Timer gives user confidence about security
- What fails: Timer can feel stressful for slow users
- Key takeaway: Show expiry timer but make it generous (2+ minutes)


2.2 UNJYNX QR CONNECTION FLOW DESIGN
--------------------------------------

For UNJYNX, QR codes serve a different purpose than login:
They connect the user's UNJYNX account to their Telegram bot.

RECOMMENDED FLOW:

Screen 1: "Connect Telegram"
- Large illustration showing phone with Telegram
- Heading: "Get reminders on Telegram"
- Subtext: "Scan this code with Telegram to connect your account"
- QR Code: Large, centered, with UNJYNX logo in center
  (Generated containing deep link: https://t.me/unjynx_bot?start=<user_token>)
- Below QR: Timer showing "Expires in 4:32"
- Below timer: Text link "Or tap to open Telegram directly"
- Bottom: "Having trouble?" link to help

Screen 2: "Confirming Connection..."
- Lottie animation: Two phones connecting with particle effects
- Text: "Waiting for confirmation from Telegram..."
- Auto-proceeds when webhook confirms

Screen 3: "Connected!"
- Success animation (checkmark with confetti)
- Channel card showing Telegram as connected
- "Send a test message" CTA button
- "Done" button to return to hub


2.3 FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
----------------------------------

- QR Generation: Use `qr_flutter` package for generating QR codes
- QR Scanning: Use `mobile_scanner` package (Google ML Kit backend)
  - Supports Android (CameraX/ML Kit), iOS (AVFoundation/Apple Vision), Web (ZXing)
  - Active development, comprehensive platform support
  - Only required parameter is `onDetect` callback
  - Manage lifecycle with MobileScannerController (autoStart: false for manual control)
- Deep Link: Generate t.me deep link with unique user token
- WebSocket: Listen for Telegram webhook confirmation to auto-advance
- Token: Generate short-lived tokens (5 min expiry) for security
- Fallback: Always offer "Open in Telegram" button as alternative to QR scan


================================================================================
SECTION 3: PHONE NUMBER INPUT & OTP VERIFICATION UX
================================================================================

3.1 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
------------------------

A) WHATSAPP PHONE VERIFICATION
- Country auto-detected from SIM card
- Country code and phone number in separate fields
- Phone number formatted as-you-type based on country rules
- OTP auto-read from SMS (no manual entry needed)
- Fallback: "Call me" option after 60 seconds
- What works: Zero-friction for most users; auto-detection is key
- What fails: Users with dual SIM sometimes get wrong country
- Key takeaway: SIM detection + manual country override

B) UBER PHONE VERIFICATION
- Minimal screen: Just phone number input + "Next" button
- 4-digit OTP code
- Auto-read with suggestion bar on iOS/Android
- Fallback options: "Resend code via SMS" and "Call me with Code"
- Timer showing when resend becomes available
- What works: Extremely minimal -- no distractions
- What fails: Short code SMS sometimes blocked by carriers
- Key takeaway: Always offer voice call as fallback

C) RAPPI PHONE VERIFICATION
- Full-screen phone input with large number pad
- Country selector with flag + dial code at the top
- Real-time validation as you type (turns green when valid)
- 6-digit OTP with auto-advance between fields
- Progress bar showing SMS delivery status
- What works: Visual feedback during the wait is reassuring
- What fails: Number pad covers too much screen on small devices
- Key takeaway: Show delivery status indicator while user waits for OTP

D) GRAB PHONE VERIFICATION
- Separate country picker screen (searchable)
- Phone number input with example formatting shown as placeholder
- "We'll send a verification code" confirmation before sending
- OTP screen with auto-fill from notification
- What works: Confirmation step prevents wasted OTP sends on typos
- What fails: Extra step adds friction for experienced users
- Key takeaway: Confirmation step is worth the trade-off for UNJYNX
  (WhatsApp/SMS messages cost money per OTP)


3.2 DESIGN RECOMMENDATIONS FOR UNJYNX
---------------------------------------

PHONE INPUT SCREEN:
- Country code auto-detected from SIM (use device locale as fallback)
- Separate country code field (tappable, opens searchable picker)
- Phone number field: right-aligned text, formatted as-you-type
- E.164 storage format (always store with country code)
- Inline validation: Red border + "Invalid phone number" below field
- Button: "Send Verification Code" (disabled until valid number)
- Pre-send confirmation: "We'll send a code to +91 98765 43210. Is this correct?"
- Privacy note: Small text below button: "We'll only use this to send reminders"

OTP INPUT SCREEN:
- 6 individual box fields (not a single text input)
- Auto-focus first box on screen load
- Auto-advance to next box on digit entry
- Auto-submit when all 6 digits entered
- Visual states: Empty (gray border) > Focused (brand purple border) > Filled (dark)
- Error state: All boxes shake + turn red + "Incorrect code, try again"
- Timer: "Resend code in 0:45" countdown
- After timer: "Resend via SMS" and "Call me instead" buttons
- SMS auto-read: Use SmartAuth/Pinput for automatic OTP detection
- Keyboard: Number-only keyboard (no decimal, no negative)


3.3 FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION
----------------------------

Phone Input Packages:
- `intl_phone_number_input`: Best overall -- Google's libphonenumber, all platforms
- `intl_phone_field`: Simpler alternative with TextFormField integration
- `country_code_picker`: For searchable country list with flags + i18n (70 languages)

OTP Input Packages:
- `pinput`: Gold standard -- 6 visual states, SMS autofill, clipboard paste, theming
  - Create defaultPinTheme, then copy for focused/submitted/error states
  - SmartAuth wrapper handles Android SMS Retriever API
  - iOS SMS autofill works natively (no extra package needed)
- `otp_pin_field`: Alternative with more animation options
- `sms_otp_auto_verify`: Dedicated auto-verify package

Auto-Fill Strategy:
- Android: SMS Retriever API via SmartAuth (no permission needed)
- iOS: Native autofill via content type `oneTimeCode` on TextField
- Fallback: Manual entry always available


================================================================================
SECTION 4: NOTIFICATION PREFERENCE SCREENS
================================================================================

4.1 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
------------------------

A) iOS NOTIFICATION SETTINGS
- App-level: Allow Notifications master toggle
- Below toggle: Lock Screen / Notification Center / Banners checkboxes
- Sound, badge, and banner style controls
- Notification grouping: Automatic / By App / Off
- Time Sensitive: Allow apps to send urgent notifications
- Scheduled Summary: Batched delivery at chosen times
- What works: Granular yet organized; progressive disclosure
- What fails: Settings are per-app; no cross-app category view
- Key takeaway: Progressive disclosure -- master toggle first, details later

B) ANDROID NOTIFICATION CHANNELS
- Per-app notification categories (e.g., "Messages", "Updates", "Promotions")
- Each category: Importance level (Urgent/High/Default/Low/None)
- Sound, vibration, and LED independently configurable per category
- Bubble support for conversations
- What works: Category system is developer-controlled (consistent UX)
- What fails: Too many categories overwhelm users
- Key takeaway: Keep categories under 8; merge similar ones

C) SLACK NOTIFICATION PREFERENCES
- Workspace-level defaults with channel exceptions
- "Notify me about": All messages OR Mentions & DMs
- Keywords: Comma-separated list of trigger words
- "My notification schedule": Work hours only
- Sound selection per notification type
- Do Not Disturb: One-click or scheduled
- What works: Keyword notifications are unique and useful
- What fails: Per-workspace settings are hard to find
- Key takeaway: Keyword-based notifications = unique feature to consider

D) TODOIST NOTIFICATION PREFERENCES
- Grid/matrix layout: Event types (rows) x Channels (columns)
- Events: Comments, Assignments, Joins, Leaves, Removals
- Channels: Email, Push
- Per-project overrides for shared projects
- Urgent Reminders: Full-screen alarm that bypasses DND (iOS)
- What works: Grid makes it easy to see everything at once
- What fails: Only 2 channel columns
- Key takeaway: UNJYNX should use the grid pattern with 5-7 channel columns

E) BASECAMP NOTIFICATION PREFERENCES
- "Work Can Wait" mode: Set work hours, no notifications outside them
- Per-user work schedule (start time, end time, working days)
- Notification bundling: Groups messages within 5-minute windows
- Focus mode: Completely disables notifications
- Quick snooze: 3-hour snooze button
- What works: "Work Can Wait" is the best-named feature in notifications
- What fails: No per-project granularity
- Key takeaway: "Work Can Wait" concept is perfect for UNJYNX task reminders


