-----------------------

Accessible via Settings > Privacy > Consent Dashboard

Shows:
- List of all purposes with current consent status (granted/withdrawn)
- Date each consent was given or withdrawn
- "Withdraw" button next to each active consent
- Withdrawal confirmation: "Are you sure? You'll stop receiving [category] notifications"
- Audit trail: Complete history of consent changes
- Export: "Download my consent history" (JSON/PDF)
- Grievance: "Report an issue with your data" link


================================================================================
SECTION 6: FALLBACK CHAIN UX (DRAG-REORDER PRIORITY)
================================================================================

6.1 CONCEPT EXPLANATION
-------------------------

A fallback chain defines the priority order in which UNJYNX tries to deliver
a notification. If the first channel fails or is unavailable, it tries the next.

Example chain: Push > WhatsApp > Telegram > Email > SMS

If push notification fails (app not installed), try WhatsApp.
If WhatsApp fails (not connected), try Telegram.
If Telegram fails (bot blocked), try Email.
If Email fails (bounced), try SMS (last resort, costs money).


6.2 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
------------------------

A) NOVU FALLBACK SYSTEM
- Visual workflow builder with nodes for each channel
- Drag-and-drop to reorder priority
- Conditional logic: "If delivered via Push, skip WhatsApp"
- Wait timers between attempts: "Wait 5 min, then try next channel"
- What works: Visual flow makes the chain intuitive
- What fails: Too complex for consumer apps
- Key takeaway: Simplify for consumer UX -- numbered list with drag handles

B) SUPRSEND MULTI-CHANNEL DELIVERY
- Channel priorities per notification category
- Automatic fallback based on delivery status
- "Intelligent routing" that learns user's preferred channel
- What works: ML-based routing adapts over time
- What fails: Black box -- users don't know why they got SMS instead of push
- Key takeaway: Show users the active chain AND which channel was used

C) COURIER NOTIFICATION ROUTING
- Routing rules: "Best of" (try all) or "Escalation" (sequential fallback)
- Per-user channel preferences influence routing
- Delivery receipts determine when to escalate
- What works: Dual mode (parallel vs sequential) is powerful
- Key takeaway: UNJYNX should offer "Simultaneous" and "Sequential" modes


6.3 DRAG-REORDER UX PATTERNS
------------------------------

PATTERN 1: DRAG HANDLE LIST
- Each channel shown as a card with drag handle (hamburger icon) on left
- Number badge showing priority (1, 2, 3...)
- Drag to reorder; numbers update automatically
- Pros: Most intuitive for mobile users
- Cons: Touch precision can be tricky on small screens
- Recommendation: PRIMARY pattern for UNJYNX

PATTERN 2: UP/DOWN ARROWS
- Each card has up-arrow and down-arrow buttons on the right
- Single tap moves item one position
- Pros: Accessible; works with screen readers
- Cons: Slower than drag for large reorders
- Recommendation: SECONDARY pattern (accessibility fallback)

PATTERN 3: NUMBER INPUT
- Each card has a number input showing its priority
- User can type a new number to reorder
- Pros: Precise control
- Cons: Unfamiliar to most mobile users
- Recommendation: NOT for UNJYNX

DESIGN DETAILS:
- Drag handle: 3 horizontal lines (hamburger), left side of card
- While dragging: Card elevates (shadow increases), slight scale up (1.02x)
- Drop zone: Colored line between cards shows where it will land
- Animation: Smooth 200ms spring animation when items shift
- Haptic: Light haptic feedback on pickup and drop
- Accessibility: Long-press to enter reorder mode, use volume buttons to move


6.4 FALLBACK CHAIN SCREEN DESIGN FOR UNJYNX
----------------------------------------------

SCREEN: "Delivery Priority"

Header: "How should we reach you?"
Subheader: "Drag to reorder. We'll try each channel in order."

[Drag Handle] 1. Push Notification    [Connected]   [Free]
[Drag Handle] 2. Telegram             [Connected]   [Free]
[Drag Handle] 3. WhatsApp             [Connected]   [Pro]
[Drag Handle] 4. Email                [Connected]   [Free]
[Drag Handle] 5. SMS                  [Not set up]  [Pro]

Delivery Mode Toggle:
  ( ) Sequential: Try one at a time, wait for delivery
  (x) Smart: AI picks the best channel based on your activity

Wait Time Between Attempts:
  [Slider: 1 min ---- 5 min ---- 15 min ---- 30 min]
  Current: 5 minutes

Bottom Card:
  "Based on your activity, Telegram works best for you at 8-10 AM
   and Push works best after 6 PM"
  [Small text] "Powered by UNJYNX AI"


6.5 FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION
----------------------------

Built-in Solution:
- `ReorderableListView` widget (Flutter built-in, Material library)
  - `ReorderableListView.builder` for large lists
  - `onReorder` callback receives oldIndex and newIndex
  - Default: Long-press to pick up on mobile, drag handles on desktop
  - `buildDefaultDragHandles: false` for custom drag handle widgets
  - `proxyDecorator` callback for custom drag appearance

Enhanced Libraries:
- `animated_reorderable_list`: Adds smooth animations during reorder
  - Derived from Flutter's native AnimatedList + ReorderableListView
  - Supports both ListView and GridView with drag-and-drop
  - Better visual transitions than built-in widget

Implementation Pattern:
  1. Store channel priorities as List<ChannelPriority> in state
  2. Use ReorderableListView.builder with proxyDecorator for elevation effect
  3. On reorder, create new immutable list with updated order
  4. Save to local storage (Drift) and sync to server
  5. Add haptic feedback via HapticFeedback.lightImpact() on drag start


================================================================================
SECTION 7: QUIET HOURS & DO NOT DISTURB UI
================================================================================

7.1 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
------------------------

A) iOS FOCUS MODES
- Multiple named profiles: Do Not Disturb, Work, Personal, Sleep, Driving, Fitness
- Custom Focus: User-created with name, color, emoji/icon
- Per-Focus allowed contacts and apps
- Time-Sensitive breakthrough: Apps can mark notifications as urgent
- Intelligent Breakthrough (Apple Intelligence): AI decides what's important
- Schedule triggers: Time, Location, App opened, Smart Activation
- Focus Filters: Per-app behavior when Focus is active
- Lock Screen customization per Focus
- Focus sharing: Show Focus status to contacts
- What works: Rich customization; automatic triggers are game-changing
- What fails: Setup complexity; many users only use Do Not Disturb
- Key takeaway: Offer 2-3 presets + custom option; auto-triggers are key

B) ANDROID DO NOT DISTURB
- Schedule-based: Day-of-week + time range
- Exception categories: Alarms, Media, Calls from contacts, Repeat callers
- Duration options: Until next alarm, For X hours/minutes, Ask every time
- Notification behavior: No sound, No vibration, No visual disturbance
- Priority mode: Only starred contacts break through
- What works: Simple schedule setup; "Until next alarm" is genius
- What fails: Limited to one DND schedule (no multiple profiles)
- Key takeaway: "Until next alarm" pattern is excellent for UNJYNX

C) SLACK DO NOT DISTURB
- Default DND hours: Set per-workspace (e.g., 6 PM - 8 AM daily)
- Recurring schedule: Choose specific days and time ranges
- Quick pause: Snooze notifications for 20min/1hr/2hr/until tomorrow
- "Set yourself as away" companion feature
- Status integration: DND status visible to teammates
- What works: Recurring schedule + quick pause covers both planned and ad-hoc
- What fails: No location-based triggers
- Key takeaway: Both scheduled AND ad-hoc quiet hours needed

D) BASECAMP "WORK CAN WAIT"
- Per-user work schedule: Start time, end time, working days
- Default: 8 AM - 6 PM in user's timezone
- Outside work hours: All notifications silenced
- Focus Mode: Complete notification disable
- Quick snooze: 3-hour snooze button
- Notification bundling: Groups within 5-minute windows
- What works: Best naming in the industry; default schedule is smart
- What fails: No per-project scheduling
- Key takeaway: Default work hours based on common patterns (editable)

E) TODOIST URGENT REMINDERS (iOS)
- Toggle "Urgent" flag on any reminder
- Triggers persistent, full-screen alarm
- Cuts through Silent mode AND Do Not Disturb
- Rings on Apple Watch
- What works: Solves the "I missed a critical deadline" problem
- What fails: Could be abused (too many urgent reminders = noise)
- Key takeaway: UNJYNX should support breakthrough for overdue HIGH priority tasks


7.2 QUIET HOURS DESIGN FOR UNJYNX
-----------------------------------

SCREEN: "Focus & Quiet Hours"

Section 1: Quick Actions
  [Chip] Do Not Disturb (Now)  [Chip] For 1 Hour  [Chip] Until Tomorrow

Section 2: Scheduled Quiet Hours
  Work Schedule:
  - Work days: [M] [T] [W] [T] [F] [ ] [ ]   (toggleable day chips)
  - Active hours: [09:00] to [18:00]           (time pickers)
  - [Toggle] Only send reminders during work hours

  Sleep Schedule:
  - Sleep time: [22:00] to [07:00]
  - [Toggle] Silence all notifications during sleep
  - [Toggle] Allow urgent task reminders to break through

Section 3: Focus Modes (Presets)
  [Card] "Deep Work"    - No notifications for 2 hours, then batch deliver
  [Card] "Meeting"      - Silence all, auto-detected from calendar
  [Card] "Weekend"      - Only urgent tasks + daily content
  [Card] "+ Custom"     - Create your own Focus mode

Section 4: Breakthrough Rules
  [Toggle] Allow overdue task reminders (always)
  [Toggle] Allow urgent priority tasks
  [Toggle] Allow team @mentions
  Time Sensitive Threshold: [Slider: 30min before due --- at due time]

Section 5: Smart Schedule (AI)
  [Toggle] Let UNJYNX learn your best notification times
  "Based on 2 weeks of data, your optimal notification windows are:
   Morning: 8:15 - 9:30 AM  |  Afternoon: 1:00 - 2:15 PM  |  Evening: 6:30 - 7:45 PM"


7.3 IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
--------------------------

- Store schedules in RRULE format (RFC 5545) for recurring patterns
- Use device timezone (with option to override for travelers)
- Calendar integration: Read calendar events for auto-DND during meetings
- Snooze implementation: Store snooze_until timestamp, compare on notification send
- Breakthrough logic: Server-side evaluation of task priority vs user's DND rules
- Notification bundling: BullMQ delayed jobs, batch deliver after quiet hours end
- Widget: Show current Focus status on home screen widget


================================================================================
SECTION 8: PREMIUM BADGE & TIER GATING UI PATTERNS
================================================================================

8.1 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
------------------------

A) SPOTIFY FREE vs PREMIUM
- Free users see features but with overlay: "Upgrade to Premium"
- Tap locked feature: Bottom sheet with benefits + pricing
- Premium badge: Green checkmark next to "Premium" in profile
- Shuffle limitation: "Play any song" shown with lock icon
- What works: Features are visible but gated -- shows value before asking
- What fails: Too aggressive ads for premium in free tier
- Key takeaway: Show features, gate actions -- not visibility

B) CANVA PRO
- Templates show small crown icon for Pro-only items
- Pro badge: Gold crown overlaying content thumbnail
- Clicking Pro content: Modal with comparison (Free vs Pro vs Teams)
- In-context upgrade: "Unlock this [feature] with Canva Pro"
- What works: Crown is universally understood as premium
- What fails: Too many items have crowns, causing "crown blindness"
- Key takeaway: Use badges sparingly on highest-value features only

C) TODOIST PRO
- Free tier: Shows reminder feature but locked
- Subtle "PRO" label next to feature name
- Tap: Slide-up sheet explaining the feature + upgrade CTA
- Task limit: Shows "5/5 projects" with progress bar
- What works: Transparent about limits; upgrade feels natural
- What fails: Hard project limits feel punitive
- Key takeaway: Soft limits (feature quality) > hard limits (feature count)

D) NOTION
- Free tier: Guest limit shown prominently
- "Upgrade" button in sidebar with subtle highlight
- Block limit: Progress bar showing usage
- Tap locked feature: Side panel comparison of all plans
- What works: The block/guest limits are clearly communicated
- What fails: Complex plan comparison (too many tiers)
- Key takeaway: Keep tier comparison simple (2-3 plans max in upgrade sheet)

E) TELEGRAM PREMIUM
- Premium features highlighted with gradient purple/blue star icon
- Non-premium users see "2x" badges on features showing what premium unlocks
- Premium reactions: Visible to all, usable by premium only
- Animated emoji: Shows preview, locks interaction
- What works: Star icon is distinctive and desirable (aspirational design)
- What fails: Some premium features feel arbitrary
- Key takeaway: Gradient icon/badge creates aspirational premium feel


8.2 PREMIUM BADGE DESIGN FOR UNJYNX
--------------------------------------

BADGE VARIANTS:

1. CHANNEL BADGE (on channel hub cards):
   - Free channels: No badge
   - Pro channels: Small "PRO" pill badge, gradient purple-to-gold
   - Position: Top-right corner of channel card
   - Size: 28x14dp, 10sp text, border-radius 7dp
   - Light theme: Purple-900 bg, white text
   - Dark theme: Gold-400 bg, black text

2. FEATURE LOCK (on locked settings/toggles):
   - Small lock icon (16dp) replacing the toggle for locked features
   - Lock icon color: Muted gold
   - Tap lock: Slide-up upgrade sheet (not full-screen navigation)
   - Locked row opacity: 0.6 (dimmed but readable)

3. QUOTA INDICATOR (on usage screens):
   - "3/5 WhatsApp messages this month" with linear progress bar
   - Bar color: Brand purple (normal) > Warning orange (80%) > Red (100%)
   - "Upgrade for unlimited" text link below bar

4. UPGRADE SHEET (bottom sheet, not page):
   - Feature illustration at top (Lottie animation)
   - "Unlock [Feature Name]" heading
   - 3 bullet points showing what user gains
   - Price: "Rs 149/mo" with "or Rs 99/mo billed annually" below
   - [Primary Button] "Start 7-day free trial"
   - [Text Link] "View all Pro features"
   - [X] Close button (don't force interaction)


8.3 DESIGN PRINCIPLES FOR TIER GATING
---------------------------------------

DO:
- Show features exist before gating (demonstrate value)
- Use slide-up bottom sheets for upgrade prompts (not full navigation)
- Keep the upgrade CTA small and non-intrusive in regular usage
- Let users dismiss upgrade prompts easily (close button, swipe down)
- Show specific benefit of the locked feature (not generic "go premium")
- Use soft limits: Allow N free messages per month, not zero
- Celebrate when users hit milestones ("You've used 5 WhatsApp reminders!")

DON'T:
- Block core functionality behind paywall (task creation must always be free)
- Show upgrade prompts more than once per session for same feature
- Use aggressive colors (red) for premium badges (use aspirational gold/purple)
- Lock basic notification channels (push must always be free)
- Make premium features invisible to free users (they can't desire what they can't see)
- Use countdown timers or fake urgency for upgrade prompts


================================================================================
SECTION 9: CONNECTION STATUS INDICATORS
================================================================================

9.1 STATUS STATES TAXONOMY
----------------------------

Each notification channel in UNJYNX can be in one of these states:

STATE 1: NOT CONFIGURED
- Appearance: Outlined card, muted colors, "Connect" button
- Icon: Channel icon (greyed out) + plus badge
- Description: User has never set up this channel
- Action: Tap to start connection flow

STATE 2: CONNECTING / PENDING
- Appearance: Card with pulsing border animation
- Icon: Channel icon + spinning indicator
- Description: Connection in progress (waiting for OTP, QR scan, etc.)
- Action: Tap to view connection progress / cancel

STATE 3: CONNECTED (ACTIVE)
- Appearance: Filled card, brand colors
- Icon: Channel icon (full color) + green dot indicator
- Description: Channel is connected and working
- Action: Tap to view settings / send test message

STATE 4: CONNECTED (PAUSED)
- Appearance: Filled card but dimmed opacity (0.7)
- Icon: Channel icon + pause badge
- Description: User has temporarily paused this channel
- Action: Tap to resume / view settings

STATE 5: ERROR / NEEDS ATTENTION
- Appearance: Card with warning orange border
- Icon: Channel icon + warning triangle badge
- Description: Connection issue (token expired, bot blocked, etc.)
- Action: Tap to see error details + fix/reconnect

STATE 6: DISCONNECTED
- Appearance: Card with subtle red accent
- Icon: Channel icon (greyed) + red X badge
- Description: Channel was connected but has been disconnected
- Action: Tap to reconnect


9.2 REAL-WORLD REFERENCE PATTERNS
-----------------------------------

A) GOOGLE ACCOUNT CONNECTED APPS
- Green checkmark for connected services
- Yellow warning for services needing attention
- "Last synced 2 hours ago" timestamp
- What works: Clear visual hierarchy with color coding
- Key takeaway: Show last-sync timestamp for confidence

B) IFTTT SERVICE CONNECTIONS
- Connected: Colored service icon with "Connected" badge
- Error: Red alert banner at top of service card
- Reconnect: Blue "Reconnect" button inline
- What works: Error states are prominent without being alarming
- Key takeaway: Use inline reconnect buttons, not separate screens

C) ZAPIER INTEGRATION STATUS
- Green dot: Active and running
- Yellow dot: Needs attention (e.g., re-authenticate)
- Red dot: Broken/disconnected
- Gray dot: Paused by user
- What works: Simple dot system is universally understood
- Key takeaway: Colored dots are the most compact status indicator

D) SLACK WORKSPACE STATUS
- Green dot: Active
- Yellow dot: Away
- Red dot: Do Not Disturb
- Gray ring: Offline
- What works: Consistent across all of Slack's UI
- Key takeaway: Status dot system should be consistent app-wide

E) CARBON DESIGN SYSTEM STATUS INDICATORS
- Different shapes AND colors for accessibility (not color-only)
- Icon indicators: checkmark (success), warning triangle, error circle, info
- Semantic grouping: informational, positive, warning, negative
- Key takeaway: Always pair color with icon shape for color-blind users


9.3 IMPLEMENTATION FOR UNJYNX
-------------------------------

Status Dot Component:
- Size: 10dp diameter, positioned bottom-right of channel icon
- Green (#4CAF50): Connected & active
- Amber (#FF9800): Needs attention / connecting
- Red (#F44336): Error / disconnected
- Gray (#9E9E9E): Not configured / paused
- Pulsing animation for "connecting" state (scale 1.0 to 1.3, 1.5s loop)
- Border: 2dp white border (creates contrast on any background)

Channel Card Component:
  +-----------------------------------------------+
  | [Icon]  Channel Name           [Status Dot]   |
  |         Connection status text                 |
  |         Last used: 2 hours ago                 |
  |                                  [Pro Badge]   |
  +-----------------------------------------------+

- Icon: 40dp channel logo (full color when connected, grayscale otherwise)
- Title: Channel name (16sp, medium weight)
- Subtitle: Status text (14sp, secondary color)
- Trailing: Status dot + optional Pro badge
- Background: Surface container (M3) with state-appropriate tint
- Border: 1dp outline (color varies by state)
- Tap: Navigate to channel detail / connection flow
- Long press: Quick actions (test, pause, disconnect)

Flutter Implementation:
- Custom StatelessWidget wrapping Material 3 Card
- AnimationController for pulsing dot (connecting state)
- ColorTween for smooth state transitions
- Use `connectivity_plus` to auto-detect network issues
- Poll channel health endpoint every 5 minutes (background)
- Show last-successful-delivery timestamp


================================================================================
SECTION 10: CHANNEL USAGE & QUOTA VISUALIZATION
================================================================================

10.1 REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES
--------------------------

A) MOBILE DATA USAGE (iOS / ANDROID)
- Circular arc showing usage vs limit
- Color transitions: Green > Yellow > Orange > Red as usage increases
- Breakdown list below arc showing per-app usage
- Widget version: Compact circle on home screen
- What works: Arc immediately communicates ratio at a glance
- Key takeaway: Arc/gauge for overall, list for breakdown

B) GITHUB ACTIONS USAGE
- Linear progress bar per category (minutes, storage, packages)
- Percentage label on the right
- Color: Green < 50%, Yellow 50-80%, Red > 80%
- "Included" vs "Paid" usage clearly separated
- What works: Linear bars with percentage are very scannable
- Key takeaway: Show "included" vs "additional" cost clearly

C) VERCEL BANDWIDTH/USAGE
- Clean card with circular progress ring
- Large number in center: "1.2 GB of 100 GB"
- Small percentage below: "1.2%"
- Daily/monthly toggle
- What works: Large prominent number is immediately useful
- Key takeaway: Show absolute numbers AND percentage

D) TWILIO CONSOLE
- Message count: "1,247 of 5,000 messages sent"
- Per-channel breakdown: SMS (500), WhatsApp (300), Email (447)
- Cost display: "$12.47 this month"
- Rate card: Shows per-message cost for each channel
- What works: Combining count with cost makes users aware of spending
- Key takeaway: Show cost impact alongside usage for premium channels

E) APPLE STORAGE MANAGEMENT
- Stacked horizontal bar showing category breakdown by color
- List below with category name, color swatch, and size
- Recommendations section: "You could save X by..."
- What works: Stacked bar instantly shows proportions
- Key takeaway: Use stacked bar for channel proportion comparison


10.2 QUOTA VISUALIZATION DESIGN FOR UNJYNX
---------------------------------------------

SCREEN: "Usage & Quotas"

Section 1: Monthly Overview Card
  +--------------------------------------------------+
  |  [Circular Progress Ring - 65% filled]           |
  |       327 / 500                                  |
  |     messages sent                                |
  |   Resets in 12 days                              |
  |   [Upgrade for unlimited]                        |
  +--------------------------------------------------+

Section 2: Per-Channel Breakdown
  Push Notifications     [==========----] 215   Unlimited
