14.1 COMPETITIVE ADVANTAGES TO BUILD
--------------------------------------

Based on this research, UNJYNX should implement these differentiating features:

1. NOTIFICATION MODE PRESETS (inspired by iOS Focus + Basecamp)
   - "Calm Mode": Push only, daily digest, quiet hours 10PM-8AM
   - "Regular Mode": Push + Telegram, immediate for high priority, digest for rest
   - "Power User Mode": All channels, immediate delivery, AI-optimized timing
   - Custom mode: Full control over every setting
   -- No competitor offers this in a task management app

2. AI-OPTIMIZED DELIVERY TIMING (inspired by Apple Intelligence)
   - Track when user actually reads/acts on notifications
   - Build per-user optimal delivery time model
   - "Smart Schedule" shows learned time windows
   - Per-channel optimization (user may check Telegram at different times than email)
   -- Only Apple does this natively; no third-party task app has it

3. NOTIFICATION MATRIX VIEW (inspired by Todoist + SuprSend)
   - Grid: Event categories x Channels
   - Tap cell to toggle, long-press for frequency sub-menu
   - Tap column header for bulk channel control
   - Switch between category-first and channel-first views
   -- Most apps offer one view; UNJYNX offers both

4. VISUAL FALLBACK CHAIN (inspired by Novu + Courier)
   - Drag-to-reorder with smooth animations
   - Real-time "last used" indicators
   - AI recommendation: "Based on your activity, Telegram works best at 8 AM"
   - Wait time slider between attempts
   -- No consumer task app exposes fallback logic to users

5. CONTEXTUAL CONSENT (inspired by DPDP + GDPR best practices)
   - Per-purpose granular toggles with plain language descriptions
   - Multilingual (22 Indian languages from day one)
   - Consent dashboard with withdrawal history
   - TRAI DLT compliance built into SMS/WhatsApp flows
   -- Compliance as a feature, not an afterthought

6. USAGE QUOTA GAMIFICATION
   - "You've sent 327 reminders this month -- that's 42% more than last month!"
   - Channel efficiency score: "WhatsApp reminders are opened 3x faster"
   - Cost transparency: "Your WhatsApp usage costs Rs 0 (3/5 free messages used)"
   -- Turns quota limits into engagement metrics

7. FRIEND FIRST INSTAGRAM CONNECTION
   - Unique flow: UNJYNX official page sends follow request
   - User accepts follow on Instagram
   - Messenger API enables direct messaging
   - Daily content keeps 24h messaging window alive
   -- No competitor has this; completely novel approach

8. KEYWORD NOTIFICATIONS (inspired by Slack)
   - Users define trigger keywords for team notifications
   - "Notify me when anyone mentions 'deploy', 'urgent', or my name"
   - Works across all connected team projects
   -- Unique in task management apps


14.2 SCREEN FLOW ARCHITECTURE
-------------------------------

ONBOARDING FLOW (First-time setup):
1. Welcome > 2. Choose Mode (Calm/Regular/Power) > 3. Connect First Channel
4. Consent Screen > 5. Quiet Hours Quick Setup > 6. Done

CHANNEL CONNECTION FLOWS:

Push Notifications:
  1. Permission request (contextual, not on first launch)
  2. OS dialog
  3. Success/failure handling
  Timeline: 5 seconds

Telegram (FREE - implement first):
  1. "Connect Telegram" screen with QR code + "Open in Telegram" button
  2. QR contains: t.me/unjynx_bot?start=<token>
  3. User scans or taps > Opens Telegram > Sends /start to bot
  4. Bot webhook confirms connection
  5. Success screen with test message CTA
  Timeline: 30 seconds

Email:
  1. Enter email address (pre-filled from account if available)
  2. Verification email sent
  3. User clicks link in email OR enters 6-digit code from email
  4. Email confirmed
  Timeline: 1-2 minutes

WhatsApp (Pro feature, uses Gupshup BSP):
  1. Upgrade prompt (if free tier) OR direct to setup (if Pro)
  2. Enter phone number (reuse account phone if available)
  3. Consent screen: TRAI compliance + purpose explanation
  4. OTP verification via WhatsApp message
  5. Template approval status shown
  6. Test message sent
  Timeline: 2-3 minutes (first time includes Gupshup approval wait)

SMS (Pro feature, uses MSG91):
  1. Upgrade prompt (if free tier) OR direct to setup
  2. Enter phone number (reuse account phone)
  3. Consent screen: TRAI DLT compliance explanation
  4. OTP via SMS
  5. DND registry check: "Your number may be registered for DND"
  6. If DND: Explain limitations, suggest Telegram/WhatsApp instead
  7. Test message sent
  Timeline: 1-2 minutes

Instagram (Friend First approach):
  1. Explain "Friend First" approach with illustration
  2. Show UNJYNX official Instagram QR code / link
  3. User follows UNJYNX page on Instagram
  4. Webhook detects new follower
  5. UNJYNX sends welcome message via Messenger API
  6. User confirms in-app
  7. Daily content keeps 24h window alive
  Timeline: 1-5 minutes (depends on Instagram follow speed)

Discord:
  1. OAuth2 flow: "Connect with Discord" button
  2. Discord authorization screen (in-app browser)
  3. Select server and channel for notifications
  4. Bot joins server (if not already there)
  5. Test message sent to selected channel
  Timeline: 1-2 minutes

Slack:
  1. OAuth2 flow: "Connect with Slack" button
  2. Slack authorization screen
  3. Select workspace and channel
  4. Bot posts introduction message
  5. Test notification sent
  Timeline: 1-2 minutes


14.3 DATA MODELS (DRIFT / DRIZZLE)
-------------------------------------

Local (Drift - Flutter):
- channels: id, type, status, config_json, last_sync, error_message, priority_order
- notification_preferences: id, category_id, channel_id, enabled, frequency
- quiet_hours_config: id, profile_name, work_days, work_start, work_end, etc.
- consent_records: id, purpose, granted, granted_at, version, ip_address
- usage_stats: id, channel_id, period_start, messages_sent, messages_limit

Server (Drizzle - PostgreSQL):
- notification_channels: Same as local + profile_id FK
- notification_preferences: Same as local + profile_id FK
- quiet_hours_profiles: Multiple profiles per user
- consent_audit_log: Immutable log of all consent changes (DPDP requirement)
- channel_usage: Aggregated per-channel per-month stats
- delivery_log: Every notification attempt with status, channel, latency


14.4 NOTIFICATION ORCHESTRATION FLOW
--------------------------------------

When UNJYNX needs to send a notification:

1. EVENT TRIGGER: Task due, content ready, team update, etc.

2. PREFERENCE CHECK:
   - Is user in quiet hours? >> Queue for later
   - Is this category enabled for user? >> Skip if disabled
   - Does user have consent for this purpose? >> Skip if no consent

3. CHANNEL SELECTION (Fallback Chain):
   - Get user's ordered channel list
   - Filter to channels that are: connected + category-enabled + within quota
   - If "Smart" mode: AI selects optimal channel based on time + history
   - If "Sequential" mode: Try first available channel

4. DELIVERY ATTEMPT:
   - Push: FCM/APNs via awesome_notifications
   - Telegram: Bot API (free, unlimited)
   - WhatsApp: Gupshup BSP template message
   - Email: SendGrid API
   - SMS: MSG91/Kaleyra API
   - Instagram: Messenger API (within 24h window)
   - Discord: Bot webhook
   - Slack: Bot webhook

5. DELIVERY TRACKING:
   - Record attempt in delivery_log
   - Wait for delivery receipt (channel-specific timeout)
   - If failed: Try next channel in fallback chain
   - If all channels failed: Queue for retry with backoff

6. USAGE UPDATE:
   - Increment usage counter for channel
   - Check against quota limits
   - If approaching limit: Show in-app warning
   - If limit reached: Skip paid channels, use free alternatives


14.5 ACCESSIBILITY REQUIREMENTS
----------------------------------

- All toggles: Labeled with semanticLabel for screen readers
- Status dots: Accompanied by text description (not color-only)
- Drag reorder: Support keyboard navigation (arrow keys) as alternative
- QR code: Always provide text/link alternative ("Open in Telegram" button)
- OTP: Support paste from clipboard for users who can't use auto-fill
- Contrast: All text meets WCAG 2.1 AA (4.5:1 for normal, 3:1 for large)
- Touch targets: Minimum 48x48dp for all interactive elements
- Reduce motion: Respect device "reduce motion" setting for animations
- Multilingual: Support right-to-left (RTL) layouts for applicable languages
- Screen reader: All cards announce channel name + status + tier in one phrase
- Focus order: Logical tab order through settings (top-to-bottom, left-to-right)


14.6 PERFORMANCE CONSIDERATIONS
----------------------------------

- Channel status polling: Every 5 minutes (not real-time, to save battery)
- Preference matrix: Load lazily (categories first, expand channels on demand)
- Usage stats: Cache locally, sync every 15 minutes
- QR code: Generate once, cache until expiry
- Channel icons: Pre-loaded SVG assets (not network images)
- Animations: Use RepaintBoundary to isolate animated widgets
- List rendering: Use ListView.builder (never ListView with children list)
- State: Use Riverpod select() to minimize rebuilds on preference changes
- Images: Use cached_network_image for any channel logos loaded from network
- Drift queries: Use watch() for reactive updates, not polling the database


